1

00:00:00,020  -->  00:00:03,955
In this video, we want to look at the final aspect

2

00:00:03,955  -->  00:00:08,344
used to describe quantitative variables, Outliers.

3

00:00:08,344  -->  00:00:13,805
Outliers are data points that fall very far from the rest of the values in our data set.

4

00:00:13,805  -->  00:00:17,550
In order to determine what is very far,

5

00:00:17,550  -->  00:00:19,715
there are a number of different methods.

6

00:00:19,715  -->  00:00:24,180
My usual method for detecting outliers isn't very scientific.

7

00:00:24,180  -->  00:00:27,420
Usually, I just look at a histogram and see if

8

00:00:27,420  -->  00:00:31,665
the point is really far from any of the other data points.

9

00:00:31,665  -->  00:00:34,470
Again, a quick plot of your data can

10

00:00:34,470  -->  00:00:38,160
often help you understand a lot in a short amount of time.

11

00:00:38,160  -->  00:00:41,460
In order to illustrate the impact that outliers can

12

00:00:41,460  -->  00:00:45,000
have on the way we report summary statistics,

13

00:00:45,000  -->  00:00:48,085
let's consider the salaries of entrepreneurs.

14

00:00:48,085  -->  00:00:51,720
Imagine I select ten entrepreneur earnings and I

15

00:00:51,720  -->  00:00:55,615
pull these nine values here as earnings in thousands of dollars,

16

00:00:55,615  -->  00:00:58,950
and the tenth is the CEO of Facebook.

17

00:00:58,950  -->  00:01:02,985
According to a post by CNN in 2016,

18

00:01:02,985  -->  00:01:09,410
he earned 4.4 million dollars per day.

19

00:01:09,410  -->  00:01:13,100
Here, we can calculate the mean of these salaries for

20

00:01:13,100  -->  00:01:19,435
entrepreneurs based on this data to be approximately 160 million dollars.

21

00:01:19,435  -->  00:01:21,590
This is incredibly misleading.

22

00:01:21,590  -->  00:01:25,760
Literally zero of the entrepreneurs earned this salary.

23

00:01:25,760  -->  00:01:29,720
None of the ten salaries are even close to this amount.

24

00:01:29,720  -->  00:01:32,905
A better measure of center would certainly be the median.

25

00:01:32,905  -->  00:01:37,370
The median here is calculated at 62,000 dollars a year and is

26

00:01:37,370  -->  00:01:43,070
a better indication of what an entrepreneur is likely to earn based on our data.

27

00:01:43,070  -->  00:01:46,895
Our standard deviation is also not a great measure in this case.

28

00:01:46,895  -->  00:01:50,380
At approximately 482 million dollars,

29

00:01:50,380  -->  00:01:55,455
all this suggests is that our earnings for entrepreneurs are really spread out,

30

00:01:55,455  -->  00:01:57,915
but that really isn't fair either.

31

00:01:57,915  -->  00:02:01,675
Just one point is really far from the rest.

32

00:02:01,675  -->  00:02:04,380
Like really really far.
